[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] One major practical drawback is its $O(b^{d})$ space complexity where d is the depth of the shallowest solution (the length of the shortest path from the source node to any given goal node) and b is the branching factor (the maximum number of successors for any given state).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] In practical travel-routing systems, it is generally outperformed by algorithms that can pre-process the graph to attain better performance, as well as by memory-bounded approaches; however, A* is still the best solution in many cases.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart, Nils Nilsson and Bertram Raphael of Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) first published the algorithm in 1968.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] It can be seen as an extension of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* achieves better performance by using heuristics to guide its search.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm terminates once it finds the shortest path to a specified goal, rather than generating the entire shortest-path tree from a specified source to all possible goals.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* was created as part of the Shakey project, which had the aim of building a mobile robot that could plan its own actions.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Nils Nilsson originally proposed using the Graph Traverser algorithm for Shakey's path planning.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Graph Traverser is guided by a heuristic function *h*(*n*), the estimated distance from node n to the goal node: it entirely ignores *g*(*n*), the distance from the start node to n.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Bertram Raphael suggested using the sum, *g*(*n*) + *h*(*n*).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart invented the concepts we now call admissibility and consistency of heuristic functions.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* was originally designed for finding least-cost paths when the cost of a path is the sum of its costs, but it has been shown that A* can be used to find optimal paths for any problem satisfying the conditions of a cost algebra.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The original 1968 A* paper contained a theorem stating that no A*-like algorithm could expand fewer nodes than A* if the heuristic function is consistent and A*'s tie-breaking rule is suitably chosen.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* is an informed search algorithm, or a best-first search, meaning that it is formulated in terms of weighted graphs: starting from a specific starting node of a graph, it aims to find a path to the given goal node having the smallest cost (least distance travelled, shortest time, etc.).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] It does this by maintaining a tree of paths originating at the start node and extending those paths one edge at a time until the goal node is reached.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] At each iteration of its main loop, A* needs to determine which of its paths to extend.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] It does so based on the cost of the path and an estimate of the cost required to extend the path all the way to the goal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] where n is the next node on the path, *g*(*n*) is the cost of the path from the start node to n, and *h*(*n*) is a heuristic function that estimates the cost of the cheapest path from n to the goal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The heuristic function is problem-specific.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Typical implementations of A* use a priority queue to perform the repeated selection of minimum (estimated) cost nodes to expand.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] This priority queue is known as the *open set*, *fringe* or *frontier*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] At each step of the algorithm, the node with the lowest *f*(*x*) value is removed from the queue, the f and g values of its neighbors are updated accordingly, and these neighbors are added to the queue.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm continues until a removed node (thus the node with the lowest f value out of all fringe nodes) is a goal node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The f value of that goal is then also the cost of the shortest path, since h at the goal is zero in an admissible heuristic.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm described so far only gives the length of the shortest path.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] To find the actual sequence of steps, the algorithm can be easily revised so that each node on the path keeps track of its predecessor.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] After this algorithm is run, the ending node will point to its predecessor, and so on, until some node's predecessor is the start node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] As an example, when searching for the shortest route on a map, *h*(*x*) might represent the straight-line distance to the goal, since that is physically the smallest possible distance between any two points.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] For a grid map from a video game, using the Taxicab distance or the Chebyshev distance becomes better depending on the set of movements available (4-way or 8-way).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic h satisfies the additional condition *h*(*x*) ≤ *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) for every edge (*x*, *y*) of the graph (where d denotes the length of that edge), then h is called monotone, or consistent.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] With a consistent heuristic, A* is guaranteed to find an optimal path without processing any node more than once and A* is equivalent to running Dijkstra's algorithm with the reduced cost *d'*(*x*, *y*) = *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) − *h*(*x*).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm has real-world applications.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] In this example, edges are railroads and h(x) is the great-circle distance (the shortest possible distance on a sphere) to the target.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm is searching for a path between Washington, D.C., and Los Angeles.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] There are a number of simple optimizations or implementation details that can significantly affect the performance of an A* implementation.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The first detail to note is that the way the priority queue handles ties can have a significant effect on performance in some situations.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] If ties are broken so the queue behaves in a LIFO manner, A* will behave like depth-first search among equal cost paths (avoiding exploring more than one equally optimal solution).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] When a path is required at the end of the search, it is common to keep with each node a reference to that node's parent.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] At the end of the search, these references can be used to recover the optimal path.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] If these references are being kept then it can be important that the same node doesn't appear in the priority queue more than once (each entry corresponding to a different path to the node, and each with a different cost).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A standard approach here is to check if a node about to be added already appears in the priority queue.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] If it does, then the priority and parent pointers are changed to correspond to the lower-cost path.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A standard binary heap based priority queue does not directly support the operation of searching for one of its elements, but it can be augmented with a hash table that maps elements to their position in the heap, allowing this decrease-priority operation to be performed in logarithmic time.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Alternatively, a Fibonacci heap can perform the same decrease-priority operations in constant amortized time.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm, as another example of a uniform-cost search algorithm, can be viewed as a special case of A* where ⁠ $h(x)=0$ ⁠ for all *x*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] General depth-first search can be implemented using A* by considering that there is a global counter *C* initialized with a very large value.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Every time we process a node we assign *C* to all of its newly discovered neighbors.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] After every single assignment, we decrease the counter *C* by one.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Thus the earlier a node is discovered, the higher its ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Both Dijkstra's algorithm and depth-first search can be implemented more efficiently without including an ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value at each node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] On finite graphs with non-negative edge weights A* is guaranteed to terminate and is *complete*, i.e. it will always find a solution (a path from start to goal) if one exists.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] On infinite graphs with a finite branching factor and edge costs that are bounded away from zero ( ${\textstyle d(x,y)>\varepsilon >0}$ for some fixed $\varepsilon$ ), A* is guaranteed to terminate only if there exists a solution.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A search algorithm is said to be *admissible* if it is guaranteed to return an optimal solution.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic function used by A* is admissible, then A* is admissible.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Call a node *closed* if it has been visited and is not in the open set.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] We *close* a node when we remove it from the open set.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A basic property of the A* algorithm, which we'll sketch a proof of below, is that when ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate (lower bound) of the true distance from the start to the goal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] So when the goal node, ⁠ g ⁠, is closed, ⁠ $f(g)$ ⁠ is no more than the true distance.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, it is no less than the true distance, since it is the length of a path to the goal plus a heuristic term.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Now we'll see that whenever a node ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ P ⁠ be an optimal path from the start to the goal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ p ⁠ be the last closed node on ⁠ P ⁠ for which ⁠ $g(p)$ ⁠ is the true distance from the start to ⁠ p ⁠ (the start is one such vertex).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The next node in ⁠ P ⁠ has the correct ⁠ g ⁠ value, since it was updated when ⁠ p ⁠ was closed, and it is open since it is not closed.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The definitive study of the optimal efficiency of A* is due to Rina Dechter and Judea Pearl.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] They considered a variety of definitions of **Alts** and **P** in combination with A*'s heuristic being merely admissible or being both consistent and admissible.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The most interesting positive result they proved is that A*, with a consistent heuristic, is optimally efficient with respect to all admissible A*-like search algorithms on all "non-pathological" search problems.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Roughly speaking, their notion of the non-pathological problem is what we now mean by "up to tie-breaking".
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] This result does not hold if A*'s heuristic is admissible but not consistent.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] In that case, Dechter and Pearl showed there exist admissible A*-like algorithms that can expand arbitrarily fewer nodes than A* on some non-pathological problems.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Optimal efficiency is about the *set* of nodes expanded, not the *number* of node expansions (the number of iterations of A*'s main loop).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] When the heuristic being used is admissible but not consistent, it is possible for a node to be expanded by A* many times, an exponential number of times in the worst case.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] In such circumstances, Dijkstra's algorithm could outperform A* by a large margin.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] While the admissibility criterion guarantees an optimal solution path, it also means that A* must examine all equally meritorious paths to find the optimal path.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] To compute approximate shortest paths, it is possible to speed up the search at the expense of optimality by relaxing the admissibility criterion.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Oftentimes we want to bound this relaxation, so that we can guarantee that the solution path is no worse than (1 + *ε*) times the optimal solution path.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] This new guarantee is referred to as *ε*-admissible.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] As a heuristic search algorithm, the performance of A* is heavily influenced by the quality of the heuristic function ${\textstyle h(n)}$ .
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic closely approximates the true cost to the goal, A* can significantly reduce the number of node expansions.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, a poor heuristic can lead to many unnecessary expansions.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] In the worst case, A* expands all nodes ${\textstyle n}$ for which ${\textstyle f(n)=g(n)+h(n)\leq C^{*}}$ , where ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ is the cost of the optimal goal node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Suppose there is a node ${\textstyle N'}$ in the open list with ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , and it's the next node to be expanded.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Since the goal node has ${\textstyle f(goal)=g(goal)+h(goal)=g(goal)=C^{*}}$ , and ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , the goal node will have a lower f-value and will be expanded before ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, A* never expands nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)>C^{*}}$ .
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Assume there exists an optimal algorithm that expands fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case using the same heuristic.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] That means there must be some node ${\textstyle N'}$ such that ${\textstyle f(N')<C^{*}}$ , yet the algorithm chooses not to expand it.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Now consider a modified graph where a new edge of cost ${\textstyle \varepsilon }$ (with ${\textstyle \varepsilon >0}$ ) is added from ${\textstyle N'}$ to the goal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] If ${\textstyle f(N')+\varepsilon <C^{*}}$ , then the new optimal path goes through ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] However, since the algorithm still avoids expanding ${\textstyle N'}$ , it will miss the new optimal path, violating its optimality.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, no optimal algorithm including A* could expand fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The worst-case complexity of A* is often described as ${\textstyle O(b^{d})}$ , where b is the branching factor and ${\textstyle d}$ is the depth of the shallowest goal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] While this gives a rough intuition, it does not precisely capture the actual behavior of A*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A more accurate bound considers the number of nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)\leq C^{*}}$ .
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] This represents both the time and space complexity in the worst case.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] The space complexity of A* is roughly the same as that of all other graph search algorithms, as it keeps all generated nodes in memory.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] In practice, this turns out to be the biggest drawback of the A* search, leading to the development of memory-bounded heuristic searches, such as Iterative deepening A*, memory-bounded A*, and SMA*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* is often used for the common pathfinding problem in applications such as video games, but was originally designed as a general graph traversal algorithm.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] It finds applications in diverse problems, including the problem of parsing using stochastic grammars in NLP.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Other cases include an Informational search with online learning.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] What sets A* apart from a greedy best-first search algorithm is that it takes the cost/distance already traveled, *g*(*n*), into account.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] Some common variants of Dijkstra's algorithm can be viewed as a special case of A* where the heuristic $h(n)=0$ for all nodes; in turn, both Dijkstra and A* are special cases of dynamic programming.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* itself is a special case of a generalization of branch and bound.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* is similar to beam search except that beam search maintains a limit on the numbers of paths that it has to explore.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/a-search-algorithm] A* can also be adapted to a bidirectional search algorithm, but special care needs to be taken for the stopping criterion.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path from a given source node to every other node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be used to find the shortest path to a specific destination node, by terminating the algorithm after determining the shortest path to that node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the nodes of the graph represent cities, and the costs of edges represent the distances between pairs of cities connected by a direct road, then Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest route between one city and all other cities.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A common application of shortest path algorithms is network routing protocols, most notably IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) and OSPF (Open Shortest Path First).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It is also employed as a subroutine in algorithms such as Johnson's algorithm.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm uses a min-priority queue data structure for selecting the shortest paths known so far.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Before more advanced priority queue structures were discovered, Dijkstra's original algorithm ran in $\Theta (|V|^{2})$ time, where $|V|$ is the number of nodes.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Fredman & Tarjan 1984 proposed a Fibonacci heap priority queue to optimize the running time complexity to $\Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ , where $|E|$ is the number of edges.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is asymptotically the fastest known single-source shortest-path algorithm for arbitrary directed graphs with unbounded non-negative weights.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, specialized cases (such as bounded/integer weights, directed acyclic graphs etc.) can be improved further.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If preprocessing is allowed, algorithms such as contraction hierarchies can be up to seven orders of magnitude faster.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is commonly used on graphs where the edge weights are positive integers or real numbers.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be generalized to any graph where the edge weights are partially ordered, provided the subsequent labels (a subsequent label is produced when traversing an edge) are monotonically non-decreasing.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In many fields, particularly artificial intelligence, Dijkstra's algorithm or a variant offers a uniform cost search and is formulated as an instance of the more general idea of best-first search.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] — Edsger Dijkstra, in an interview with Philip L.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra thought about the shortest path problem while working as a programmer at the Mathematical Center in Amsterdam in 1956.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He wanted to demonstrate the capabilities of the new ARMAC computer.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] His objective was to choose a problem and a computer solution that non-computing people could understand.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He designed the shortest path algorithm and later implemented it for ARMAC for a slightly simplified transportation map of 64 cities in the Netherlands (he limited it to 64, so that 6 bits would be sufficient to encode the city number).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A year later, he came across another problem advanced by hardware engineers working on the institute's next computer: minimize the amount of wire needed to connect the pins on the machine's back panel.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As a solution, he re-discovered Prim's minimal spanning tree algorithm (known earlier to Jarník, and also rediscovered by Prim).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra published the algorithm in 1959, two years after Prim and 29 years after Jarník.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm requires a starting node, and computes the shortest distance from that starting node to each other node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assign to every node a distance from start value: for the starting node, it is zero, and for all other nodes, it is infinity, since initially no path is known to these nodes.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] During execution, the distance of a node *N* is the length of the shortest path discovered so far between the starting node and *N*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the unvisited set, select the current node to be the one with the smallest (finite) distance; initially, this is the starting node (distance zero).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the unvisited set is empty, or contains only nodes with infinite distance (which are unreachable), then the algorithm terminates by skipping to step 6.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the only concern is the path to a target node, the algorithm terminates once the current node is the target node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the current node, consider all of its unvisited neighbors and update their distances through the current node; compare the newly calculated distance to the one currently assigned to the neighbor and assign the smaller one to it.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the current node *A* is marked with a distance of 6, and the edge connecting it with its neighbor *B* has length 2, then the distance to *B* through *A* is 6 + 2 = 8.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If B was previously marked with a distance greater than 8, then update it to 8 (the path to B through A is shorter).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Otherwise, keep its current distance (the path to B through A is not the shortest).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After considering all of the current node's unvisited neighbors, the current node is removed from the unvisited set.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Thus a visited node is never rechecked, which is correct because the distance recorded on the current node is minimal (as ensured in step 3), and thus final.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once the loop exits (steps 3–5), every visited node contains its shortest distance from the starting node.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The shortest path between two intersections on a city map can be found by this algorithm using pencil and paper.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every intersection is listed on a separate line: one is the starting point and is labeled (given a distance of) 0.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every other intersection is initially labeled with a distance of infinity.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is done to note that no path to these intersections has yet been established.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At each iteration one intersection becomes the current intersection.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the first iteration, this is the starting point.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the current intersection, the distance to every neighbor (directly-connected) intersection is assessed by summing the label (value) of the current intersection and the distance to the neighbor and then relabeling the neighbor with the lesser of that sum and the neighbor's existing label.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] I.e., the neighbor is relabeled if the path to it through the current intersection is shorter than previously assessed paths.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If so, mark the road to the neighbor with an arrow pointing to it, and erase any other arrow that points to it.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After the distances to each of the current intersection's neighbors have been assessed, the current intersection is marked as visited.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The unvisited intersection with the smallest label becomes the current intersection and the process repeats until all nodes with labels less than the destination's label have been visited.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once no unvisited nodes remain with a label smaller than the destination's label, the remaining arrows show the shortest path.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following pseudocode, dist is an array that contains the current distances from the *source* to other vertices, i.e. dist[*u*] is the current distance from the source to the vertex *u*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The prev array contains pointers to previous-hop nodes on the shortest path from source to the given vertex (equivalently, it is the *next-hop* on the path *from* the given vertex *to* the source).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The code u ← vertex in *Q* with min dist[u], searches for the vertex *u* in the vertex set *Q* that has the least dist[*u*] value.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph.Distance(*u*,*v*) returns the length of the edge joining (i.e. the distance between) the two neighbor-nodes *u* and *v*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The variable *alt* on line 14 is the length of the path from the *source* node to the neighbor node *v* if it were to go through *u*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If this path is shorter than the current shortest path recorded for *v*, then the distance of *v* is updated to *alt*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To find the shortest path between vertices *source* and *target*, the search terminates after line 10 if *u* = *target*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Now sequence *S* is the list of vertices constituting one of the shortest paths from *source* to *target*, or the empty sequence if no path exists.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A more general problem is to find all the shortest paths between *source* and *target* (there might be several of the same length).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then instead of storing only a single node in each entry of prev[] all nodes satisfying the relaxation condition can be stored.
