[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms represent the configuration space with a roadmap of sampled configurations.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] A basic algorithm samples N configurations in C, and retains those in Cfree to use as *milestones*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] A roadmap is then constructed that connects two milestones P and Q if the line segment PQ is completely in Cfree.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Again, collision detection is used to test inclusion in Cfree.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] To find a path that connects S and G, they are added to the roadmap.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] If a path in the roadmap links S and G, the planner succeeds, and returns that path.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] If not, the reason is not definitive: either there is no path in Cfree, or the planner did not sample enough milestones.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] These algorithms work well for high-dimensional configuration spaces, because unlike combinatorial algorithms, their running time is not (explicitly) exponentially dependent on the dimension of C.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] They are also (generally) substantially easier to implement.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] They are probabilistically complete, meaning the probability that they will produce a solution approaches 1 as more time is spent.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] However, they cannot determine if no solution exists.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Given basic *visibility* conditions on Cfree, it has been proven that as the number of configurations N grows higher, the probability that the above algorithm finds a solution approaches 1 exponentially.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Visibility is not explicitly dependent on the dimension of C; it is possible to have a high-dimensional space with "good" visibility or a low-dimensional space with "poor" visibility.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] The experimental success of sample-based methods suggests that most commonly seen spaces have good visibility.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] A motion planner is said to be *complete* if the planner in finite time either produces a solution or correctly reports that there is none.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Most complete algorithms are geometry-based.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] The performance of a complete planner is assessed by its computational complexity.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] When proving this property mathematically, one has to make sure, that it happens in finite time and not just in the asymptotic limit.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] This is especially problematic, if there occur infinite sequences (that converge only in the limiting case) during a specific proving technique, since then, theoretically, the algorithm will never stop.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Intuitive "tricks" (often based on induction) are typically mistakenly thought to converge, which they do only for the infinite limit.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] In other words, the solution exists, but the planner will never report it.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] This property therefore is related to Turing completeness and serves in most cases as a theoretical underpinning/guidance.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Planners based on a brute force approach are always complete, but are only realizable for finite and discrete setups.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] In practice, the termination of the algorithm can always be guaranteed by using a counter, that allows only for a maximum number of iterations and then always stops with or without solution.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] For realtime systems, this is typically achieved by using a watchdog timer, that will simply kill the process.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] The watchdog has to be independent of all processes (typically realized by low level interrupt routines).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] The asymptotic case described in the previous paragraph, however, will not be reached in this way.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] It will report the best one it has found so far (which is better than nothing) or none, but cannot correctly report that there is none.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] All realizations including a watchdog are always incomplete (except all cases can be evaluated in finite time).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Completeness can only be provided by a very rigorous mathematical correctness proof (often aided by tools and graph based methods) and should only be done by specialized experts if the application includes safety content.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] On the other hand, disproving completeness is easy, since one just needs to find one infinite loop or one wrong result returned.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Formal Verification/Correctness of algorithms is a research field on its own.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] The correct setup of these test cases is a highly sophisticated task.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Many algorithms have been developed to handle variants of this basic problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/motion-planning] Hybrid systems are those that mix discrete and continuous behavior.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] The basic idea of the occupancy grid is to represent a map of the environment as an evenly spaced field of binary random variables each representing the presence of an obstacle at that location in the environment.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] Occupancy grid algorithms compute approximate posterior estimates for these random variables.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] There are four major components of occupancy grid mapping approach.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] The goal of an occupancy mapping algorithm is to estimate the posterior probability over maps given the data: $p(m\mid z_{1:t},x_{1:t})$ , where m is the map, $z_{1:t}$ is the set of measurements from time 1 to t, and $x_{1:t}$ is the set of robot poses from time 1 to t.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] The controls and odometry data play no part in the occupancy grid mapping algorithm since the path is assumed known.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] Occupancy grid algorithms represent the map m as a fine-grained grid over the continuous space of locations in the environment.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] The most common type of occupancy grid maps are 2d maps that describe a slice of the 3d world.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] If we let $m_{i}$ denote the grid cell with index i (often in 2d maps, two indices are used to represent the two dimensions), then the notation $p(m_{i})$ represents the probability that cell i is occupied.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] The computational problem with estimating the posterior $p(m\mid z_{1:t},x_{1:t})$ is the dimensionality of the problem: if the map contains 10,000 grid cells (a relatively small map), then the number of possible maps that can be represented by this gridding is $2^{10,000}$ .
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] Thus calculating a posterior probability for all such maps is infeasible.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] Each of these estimation problems is then a binary problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] This breakdown is convenient but does lose some of the structure of the problem, since it does not enable modelling dependencies between neighboring cells.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] Due to this factorization, a binary Bayes filter can be used to estimate the occupancy probability for each grid cell.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/occupancy-grid-mapping] It is common to use a log-odds representation of the probability that each grid cell is occupied.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] The **probabilistic roadmap** planner is a motion planning algorithm in robotics, which solves the problem of determining a path between a starting configuration of the robot and a goal configuration while avoiding collisions.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] The basic idea behind PRM is to randomly sample points from the configuration space of the robot, test the samples for whether they are in the free space, and use a local planner to attempt to connect these configurations to other nearby configurations.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] The starting and goal configurations are added in, and a graph search algorithm is applied to the resulting graph to determine a path between the starting and goal configurations.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] The probabilistic roadmap planner consists of two phases: a construction and a query phase.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] In the construction phase, a roadmap (graph) is built, approximating the motions that can be made in the environment.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] First, a random configuration is created.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] Then, it is connected to some neighbors, typically either the *k* nearest neighbors or all neighbors less than some predetermined distance.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] Configurations and connections are added to the graph until the roadmap is dense enough.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] In the query phase, the start and goal configurations are connected to the graph, and the path is obtained by a Dijkstra's shortest path query.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] Given certain relatively weak conditions on the shape of the free space, PRM is provably probabilistically complete, meaning that as the number of sampled points increases without bound, the probability that the algorithm will find a path, if one exists, approaches one.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] The rate of convergence depends on certain visibility properties of the free space, where visibility is determined by the local planner.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] Roughly, if each point can "see" a large fraction of the space, and also if a large fraction of each subset of the space can "see" a large fraction of its complement, then the planner will find a path quickly.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] The invention of the PRM method is credited to Lydia E.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] There are many variants on the basic PRM method, some quite sophisticated, that vary the sampling strategy and connection strategy to achieve faster performance.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/probabilistic-roadmap] Geraerts & Overmars (2002) for a discussion.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] A **rapidly exploring random tree** (RRT) is an algorithm designed to efficiently search nonconvex, high-dimensional spaces by randomly building a space-filling tree.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] The tree is constructed incrementally from samples drawn randomly from the search space and is inherently biased to grow towards large unsearched areas of the problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] They easily handle problems with obstacles and differential constraints (nonholonomic and kinodynamic) and have been widely used in autonomous robotic motion planning.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] RRTs can be viewed as a technique to generate open-loop trajectories for nonlinear systems with state constraints.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] An RRT can also be considered as a Monte-Carlo method to bias search into the largest Voronoi regions of a graph in a configuration space.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] Some variations can even be considered stochastic fractals.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] RRTs can be used to compute approximate control policies to control high dimensional nonlinear systems with state and action constraints.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] An RRT grows a tree rooted at the starting configuration by using random samples from the search space.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] As each sample is drawn, a connection is attempted between it and the nearest state in the tree.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] If the connection is feasible (passes entirely through free space and obeys any constraints), this results in the addition of the new state to the tree.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] With uniform sampling of the search space, the probability of expanding an existing state is proportional to the size of its Voronoi region.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] As the largest Voronoi regions belong to the states on the frontier of the search, this means that the tree preferentially expands towards large unsearched areas.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] The length of the connection between the tree and a new state is frequently limited by a growth factor.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] If the random sample is further from its nearest state in the tree than this limit allows, a new state at the maximum distance from the tree along the line to the random sample is used instead of the random sample itself.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] The random samples can then be viewed as controlling the direction of the tree growth while the growth factor determines its rate.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] This maintains the space-filling bias of the RRT while limiting the size of the incremental growth.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] RRT growth can be biased by increasing the probability of sampling states from a specific area.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] Most practical implementations of RRTs make use of this to guide the search towards the planning problem goals.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] This is accomplished by introducing a small probability of sampling the goal to the state sampling procedure.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] The higher this probability, the more greedily the tree grows towards the goal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] In the algorithm above, "**RAND_CONF**" grabs a random configuration *q**rand* in *C*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] This may be replaced with a function "**RAND_FREE_CONF**" that uses samples in *C**free*, while rejecting those in *C**obs* using some collision detection algorithm.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] "**NEAREST_VERTEX**" is a function that runs through all vertices *v* in graph *G*, calculates the distance between *q**rand* and *v* using some measurement function thereby returning the nearest vertex.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] "**NEW_CONF**" selects a new configuration *q**new* by moving an incremental distance *Δq* from *q**near* in the direction of *q**rand*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] It has been shown that, under 'mild technical conditions', the cost of the best path in the RRT converges almost surely to a non-optimal value.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] For that reason, it is desirable to find variants of the RRT that converges to an optimum, like RRT*.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] Below follows is a list of RRT*-based methods (starting with RRT* itself).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/rapidly-exploring-random-tree] Not all of the derived methods do themselves converge to an optimum, though.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Although the idea of trajectory optimization has been around for hundreds of years (calculus of variations, brachistochrone problem), it only became practical for real-world problems with the advent of the computer.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Many of the original applications of trajectory optimization were in the aerospace industry, computing rocket and missile launch trajectories.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] More recently, trajectory optimization has also been used in a wide variety of industrial process and robotics applications.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Trajectory optimization first showed up in 1697, with the introduction of the brachystochrone problem: find the shape of a wire such that a bead sliding along it will move between two points in the minimum time.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The interesting thing about this problem is that it is optimizing over a curve (the shape of the wire), rather than a single number.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The most famous of the solutions was computed using calculus of variations.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] In the 1950s, the digital computer started to make trajectory optimization practical for solving real-world problems.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The first optimal control approaches grew out of the calculus of variations, based on the research of Gilbert Ames Bliss and Bryson in America, and Pontryagin in Russia.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Pontryagin's maximum principle is of particular note.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] These early researchers created the foundation of what we now call indirect methods for trajectory optimization.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Much of the early work in trajectory optimization was focused on computing rocket thrust profiles, both in a vacuum and in the atmosphere.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] This early research discovered many basic principles that are still used today.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Another successful application was the climb to altitude trajectories for the early jet aircraft.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Because of the high drag associated with the transonic drag region and the low thrust of early jet aircraft, trajectory optimization was the key to maximizing climb to altitude performance.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Optimal control based trajectories were responsible for some of the world records.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] In these situations, the pilot followed a Mach versus altitude schedule based on optimal control solutions.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] One of the important early problems in trajectory optimization was that of the singular arc, where Pontryagin's maximum principle fails to yield a complete solution.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] An example of a problem with singular control is the optimization of the thrust of a missile flying at a constant altitude and which is launched at low speed.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Here the problem is one of a bang-bang control at maximum possible thrust until the singular arc is reached.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Then the solution to the singular control provides a lower variable thrust until burnout.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] At that point bang-bang control provides that the control or thrust go to its minimum value of zero.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] This solution is the foundation of the boost-sustain rocket motor profile widely used today to maximize missile performance.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] There are a wide variety of applications for trajectory optimization, primarily in robotics: industry, manipulation, walking, path-planning, and aerospace.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] It can also be used for modeling and estimation.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Depending on the configuration, open-chain robotic manipulators require a degree of trajectory optimization.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Computing the desired path for robotic manipulators is useful in industrial manufacturing.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Trajectory optimization is used in manufacturing, particularly for controlling chemical processes.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] It has also been proposed for liquids processing, such as for evaporators or for desalination.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] There are a variety of different applications for trajectory optimization within the field of walking robotics.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] For example, one paper used trajectory optimization of bipedal gaits on a simple model to show that walking is energetically favorable for moving at a low speed and running is energetically favorable for moving at a high speed.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Like in many other applications, trajectory optimization can be used to compute a nominal trajectory, around which a stabilizing controller is built.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Trajectory optimization can be applied in detailed motion planning complex humanoid robots, such as Atlas.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Finally, trajectory optimization can be used for path-planning of robots with complicated dynamics constraints, using reduced complexity models.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Trajectory optimization is often used to compute trajectories for quadrotor helicopters.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] These applications typically used highly specialized algorithms.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] One interesting application shown by the U.Penn GRASP Lab is computing a trajectory that allows a quadrotor to fly through a hoop as it is thrown.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Another, this time by the ETH Zurich Flying Machine Arena, involves two quadrotors tossing a pole back and forth between them, with it balanced like an inverted pendulum.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The problem of computing minimum-energy trajectories for a quadcopter, has also been recently studied.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] For tactical missiles, the flight profiles are determined by the thrust and lift histories.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] These histories can be controlled by a number of means including such techniques as using an angle of attack command history or an altitude/downrange schedule that the missile must follow.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Each combination of missile design factors, desired missile performance, and system constraints results in a new set of optimal control parameters.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Guidance strategies for spacecraft are normally determined through solving a trajectory optimization problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] A thrust profile, describing the variation of the magnitude and direction of the force exerted by an onboard thruster, is computed, typically with the goal of minimizing the propellant or time required to reach a destination.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The set of unknowns to be found using optimization.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] A special type of optimization problem where the decision variables are functions, rather than real numbers.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Any optimization problem where the decision variables are real numbers.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] A class of constrained parameter optimization where either the objective function or constraints are nonlinear.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] An indirect method for solving a trajectory optimization problem proceeds in three steps: 1) Analytically construct the necessary and sufficient conditions for optimality, 2) Discretize these conditions, constructing a constrained parameter optimization problem, 3) Solve that optimization problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] A direct method for solving a trajectory optimization problem consists of two steps: 1) Discretize the trajectory optimization problem directly, converting it into a constrained parameter optimization problem, 2) Solve that optimization problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The process by which a trajectory optimization problem is converted into a parameter optimization problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] This is sometimes referred to as discretization.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Transcription methods generally fall into two categories: shooting methods and collocation methods.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] A transcription method that is based on simulation, typically using explicit Runge--Kutta schemes.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] , typically using implicit Runge--Kutta schemes.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] A transcription method that represents the entire trajectory as a single high-order orthogonal polynomial.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] After transcription, the formerly continuous trajectory is now represented by a discrete set of points, known as mesh points or grid points.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The process by which the discretization mesh is improved by solving a sequence of trajectory optimization problems.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Mesh refinement is either performed by sub-dividing a trajectory segment or by increasing the order of the polynomial representing that segment.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] can be achieved by posing it as a multi-phase trajectory optimization problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] This is done by composing a sequence of standard trajectory optimization problems that are connected using constraints.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The techniques to any optimization problems can be divided into two categories: indirect and direct.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] An indirect method works by analytically constructing the necessary and sufficient conditions for optimality, which are then solved numerically.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] A direct method attempts a direct numerical solution by constructing a sequence of continually improving approximations to the optimal solution.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The optimal control problem is an infinite-dimensional optimization problem, since the decision variables are functions, rather than real numbers.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] All solution techniques perform transcription, a process by which the trajectory optimization problem (optimizing over functions) is converted into a constrained parameter optimization problem (optimizing over real numbers).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Generally, this constrained parameter optimization problem is a non-linear program, although in special cases it can be reduced to a quadratic program or linear program.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Single shooting is the simplest type of trajectory optimization technique.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The basic idea is similar to how you would aim a cannon: pick a set of parameters for the trajectory, simulate the entire thing, and then check to see if you hit the target.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The entire trajectory is represented as a single segment, with a single constraint, known as a defect constraint, requiring that the final state of the simulation matches the desired final state of the system.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Single shooting is effective for problems that are either simple or have an extremely good initialization.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Both the indirect and direct formulation tend to have difficulties otherwise.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Multiple shooting is a simple extension to single shooting that renders it far more effective.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Rather than representing the entire trajectory as a single simulation (segment), the algorithm breaks the trajectory into many shorter segments, and a defect constraint is added between each.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The result is large sparse non-linear program, which tends to be easier to solve than the small dense programs produced by single shooting.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The particular sparsity structure can be exploited by tailored numerical solvers as implemented in the open-source software package acados.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Direct collocation methods work by approximating the state and control trajectories using polynomial splines.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] These methods are sometimes referred to as direct transcription.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] **Trapezoidal collocation** is a commonly used low-order direct collocation method.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The dynamics, path objective, and control are all represented using linear splines, and the dynamics are satisfied using trapezoidal quadrature.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] **Hermite-Simpson Collocation** is a common medium-order direct collocation method.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The state is represented by a cubic-Hermite spline, and the dynamics are satisfied using Simpson quadrature.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Orthogonal collocation is technically a subset of direct collocation, but the implementation details are so different that it can reasonably be considered its own set of methods.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Orthogonal collocation differs from direct collocation in that it typically uses high-order splines, and each segment of the trajectory might be represented by a spline of a different order.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The name comes from the use of orthogonal polynomials in the state and control splines.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] In pseudospectral discretization the entire trajectory is represented by a collection of basis functions in the time domain (independent variable).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The basis functions need not be polynomials.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Pseudospectral discretization is also known as spectral collocation.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] When used to solve a trajectory optimization problem whose solution is smooth, a pseudospectral method will achieve spectral (exponential) convergence.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] If the trajectory is not smooth, the convergence is still very fast, faster than Runge-Kutta methods.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Bless proposed a weak Hamiltonian finite element method for optimal control problems.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The idea was to derive a weak variational form of first order necessary conditions for optimality, discretise the time domain in finite intervals and use a simple zero order polynomial representation of states, controls and adjoints over each interval.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Differential dynamic programming, is a bit different than the other techniques described here.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] In particular, it does not cleanly separate the transcription and the optimization.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Instead, it does a sequence of iterative forward and backward passes along the trajectory.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Each forward pass satisfies the system dynamics, and each backward pass satisfies the optimality conditions for control.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Eventually, this iteration converges to a trajectory that is both feasible and optimal.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] In contrast to the aforementioned classical methods, generative machine learning methods may be used to generate a desirable trajectory.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] In particular, diffusion models learn to iteratively reverse a destructive forward process in which noise is added to data until it becomes noise itself by estimating the noise to remove at every time step.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Thus given easily to sample random noise as input, the diffusion process will recover a plausible corresponding noise-free data point.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Recent methods have parameterized trajectories as matrices of state-action pairs at consecutive time steps and trained a diffusion model to generate such a matrix.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] To address the issue of controllability of the generated samples, the Diffuser method proposes two techniques to steer the generated sample, thereby reducing the optimization problem to a sampling problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] First, *guided* diffusion can be used to incorporate a cost (or reward) function into the generation process.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] For this purpose the gradient of the cost function modifies the mean of the estimated noise at every time step.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Second, for motion planning problems in which the start and the end states of the trajectory are known, and the trajectory needs to comply with constraints to find a viable path, an inpainting approach can be used.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Similar to the first technique, a prior modifies the distribution of trajectories, which in this case assigns high probability to trajectories satisfying the constraints (e.g. arriving at a state s at time step t ), and zero probability to all other trajectories.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] As a result, sampling from this distribution will produce trajectories that satisfy the constraints.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] There are many techniques to choose from when solving a trajectory optimization problem.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] There is no best method, but some methods might do a better job on specific problems.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] This section provides a rough understanding of the trade-offs between methods.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] When solving a trajectory optimization problem with an indirect method, you must explicitly construct the adjoint equations and their gradients.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] This is often difficult to do, but it gives an excellent accuracy metric for the solution.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Direct methods are much easier to set up and solve, but do not have a built-in accuracy metric.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] As a result, direct methods are more widely used, especially in non-critical applications.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Indirect methods still have a place in specialized applications, particularly aerospace, where accuracy is critical.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] One place where indirect methods have particular difficulty is on problems with path inequality constraints.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] These problems tend to have solutions for which the constraint is partially active.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] When constructing the adjoint equations for an indirect method, the user must explicitly write down when the constraint is active in the solution, which is difficult to know a priori.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] One solution is to use a direct method to compute an initial guess, which is then used to construct a multi-phase problem where the constraint is prescribed.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] The resulting problem can then be solved accurately using an indirect method.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Single shooting methods are best used for problems where the control is very simple (or there is an extremely good initial guess).
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] For example, a satellite mission planning problem where the only control is the magnitude and direction of an initial impulse from the engines.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Multiple shooting tends to be good for problems with relatively simple control, but complicated dynamics.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Although path constraints can be used, they make the resulting nonlinear program relatively difficult to solve.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Direct collocation methods are good for problems where the accuracy of the control and the state are similar.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] These methods tend to be less accurate than others (due to their low-order), but are particularly robust for problems with difficult path constraints.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Orthogonal collocation methods are best for obtaining high-accuracy solutions to problems where the accuracy of the control trajectory is important.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] Some implementations have trouble with path constraints.
[src:path-planning-autonomous/trajectory-optimization] These methods are particularly good when the solution is smooth.
